SIMPLE: ebullition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ebullition
<hw>Eb`ul*li"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧bullition</ets>, L. <ets>ebullitio</ets>, fr.
<ets>ebullire</ets>. See <er>Ebullient</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
boiling or bubbling up of a liquid; the motion produced in a liquid by
its rapid conversion into vapor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Effervescence occasioned by fermentation or by any
other process which causes the liberation of a gas or an a⟦eum⟧riform
fluid, as in the mixture of an acid with a carbonated alkali.</def>
<altsp>[Formerly written <asp>bullition</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sudden burst or violent display; an outburst;
<as>as, an <ex>ebullition</ex> of anger or ill temper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eburin</ent>⟦br⟧
